{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492380"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:26:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:26:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1043"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1043"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.32,0.11,0.06,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1043"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103681"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1043"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1043"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86098"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"111"},{"type":"tags","id":"244"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9098"},{"type":"tags","id":"9099"},{"type":"tags","id":"9100"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35542"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42208"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44493"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103681"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with an 8 hour history of severe abdominal pain. The pain is constant in nature and generalised. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes and coronary artery stent insertion following a myocardial infarction four years ago. His medications include metformin, ramipril, aspirin and clopidogrel. He looks unwell, with a blood pressure of 85/64 mmHg and an irregular pulse of 110/min and temperature 37.4\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. There is generalised abdominal tenderness and guarding. All the haematological and biochemical values are within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT abdomen","CT angiography","Conventional mesenteric angiography","Laparoscopy","Laparotomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has an acute abdomen, which is a medical emergency. Whilst these clinical signs could be consistent with a perforated colon, the clinical picture is most likely to be explained by mesenteric ischaemia. Mesenteric ischaemia has a mortality rate of 60-80%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn a haemodynamically stable patient, the initial investigation to diagnose mesenteric ischaemia would be \u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiography\u003C/strong\u003E. Angiography should not be undertaken in patients with systemic manifestations of shock such as hypovolaemia and hypotension - as in this patient. Immediate surgical intervention with a \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the treatment of choice. This patient is haemodynamically unstable and has peritonitis - and this latter finding alone demands immediate surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopy \u003C/strong\u003Ecould be considered as an appropriate surgical intervention, if the abdominal signs were minimal and the diagnosis in doubt. However, this patient has peritonitis and a formal laparotomy is the correct surgical approach, facilitating intestinal resection, should it be appropriate and necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConventional mesenteric angiography \u003C/strong\u003Ewas once the standard approach, facilitating both diagnosis and treatment in one procedure, however CT angiography has now become the preferred initial investigation. There is debate as to the role of this approach in the acute setting when peritoneal signs are already present, whether immediate surgery or angiography improves survival.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen \u003C/strong\u003Eis incorrect as this does not capture images of the arteries as well as CT angio. This type of imaging will provide a general picture of the abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Identify that mesenteric ischaemia is a medical emergency and requires surgical intervention in a haemodynamically unstable patient"],"references":["Monita MM, Gonzalez L. Acute Mesenteric Ischemia. [Updated 2022 Jun 27]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK431068/","Gilani, R., Acute mesenteric arterial occlusion J. F. Eidt, J. L. Mills, \u0026amp; K. A. Collins, eds. UpToDate. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/acute-mesenteric-arterial-occlusion#! [Accessed September 16, 2022].","Tilsed JVT, Casamassima A, Kurihara H, et al. ESTES guidelines: acute mesenteric ischaemia.Eur J Trauma Emerg Surg (2016) 42:253\u2013270. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26820988/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86098"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1043"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86098"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-25T16:36:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-25T16:37:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1043"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103681"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduati